data = [
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Endoscopic adrenaline injection and heater probe application</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The endoscopy shows a bleeding duodenal ulcer (approximately in\nthe 9 o'clock position). The most appropriate initial step in\nthe management of this patient is adrenaline injection and heater\nprobe application. Peptic ulceration with stigmata of recent\nhaemorrhage should be treated with two modalities to achieve\nhaemostasis - this has been demonstrated to be significantly\nsuperior to use of only a single modality (ie adrenaline injection\nonly) in preventing rebleeding. There is no evidence to suggest the\nsuperiority of any combination of two modalities over any\nother.</p>\n\n<p>Studies have suggested that optimal treatment would now be to\ncommence IV PPI for 72 hours post injection of ulcer. In\nparticular, Lau et al. showed a decrease in recurrent bleeding,\nalthough no decrease in mortality.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Lau JY, Sung JJ, Lee KK, et al. <a href=\"http://www.nejm.org/doi/full/10.1056/NEJM200008033430501\" target=\"_blank\">Effect of intravenous omeprazole on recurrent\nbleeding after endoscopic treatment of bleeding peptic ulcers.</a>\n<cite>N Engl J Med.</cite> 2000;343:310-6.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 55-year-old male is admitted with a large haematemesis. Three\nweeks ago he underwent bilateral inguinal hernia repair and has\nbeen taking analgesia. The following image was noted on\nendoscopy.</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"asset/36.png\" width=\"400\" height=\"400\"></p>\n\n<p>Which is the most appropriate next step in the management of\nthis patient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117900\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80726\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117900\"><span>Intravenous glypressin therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117899\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80726\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117899\"><span>Endoscopic adrenaline injection and heater probe application</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117898\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80726\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117898\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Endoscopic adrenaline injection</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117901\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80726\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117901\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oral proton pump inhibitor therapy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117902\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80726\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117902\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Surgery</span></div></div>",
        "id": 132
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>0.9% sodium chloride</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The scenario is of gentleman presenting with a history and blood\ntests consistent with an upper gastrointestinal bleed. Rectal\nexamination findings suggest that there may be ongoing bleeding.\nPhysical examination findings are consistent with a diagnosis of\nchronic liver disease.</p>\n\n<p>His relative tachycardia and hypotension (with narrowing of the\npulse pressure) indicate a mild to moderate degree of <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1013\">shock</a> (would\nbe classified as grade 2). Volume replacement is indicated and\nshould be undertaken with an appropriate crystalloid or colloid\nagent. Whilst 0.9% sodium chloride is relatively contraindicated in\nchronic liver disease, due to sodium mishandling, it may be used\nwhen rapid volume expansion is required.</p>\n\n<p>Glucose/dextrose solutions are not suitable fluids for\nresuscitation due to their relatively short intravascular half\nlife.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst the haemoglobin is low it is not yet at a level which\nshould trigger transfusion (although it may fall further when\nfluids are administered to restore volume). Very early and\naggressive transfusion in patients with chronic liver disease and\nvariceal upper gastrointestinal bleeding has been associated with\nexcess mortality and rebleeding, possibly due to consequent\nincreases in portal pressure.</p>\n\n<p>The INR is 1.3, just outside the normal range and not a level at\nwhich correction by administering fresh frozen plasma would be\nwarranted - particularly in a patient who is not actively bleeding.\nAdditionally the volume of fresh frozen plasma required is unlikely\nto be adequate to expand circulating volume sufficiently.</p>\n\n<p>Given the signs and symptoms of impending hypovolaemic <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1013\">shock</a>\nelecting not to administer any fluids as part of resuscitation is\nnot an appropriate management choice.</p>\n\n<p>The table below outlines the signs and symptoms of the different\ngrades of hypovolaemic shock:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Grade 1</th>\n<td>Up to about 15% loss of effective blood volume (~750ml in an\naverage adult who is assumed to have a blood volume of 5 litres).\nThis leads to a mild resting tachycardia and can be well tolerated\nin otherwise healthy individuals. In the elderly or those with\nunderlying conditions such as ischaemic heart disease the\nadditional myocardial oxygen demands may not be tolerated so\nwell.</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Grade 2</th>\n<td>Between 15-30% loss of blood volume (750-1500ml) will provoke a\nmoderate tachycardia and begin to narrow the pulse pressure. The\ncapillary refill time will be extended.</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Grade 3</th>\n<td>At 30 - 40% loss of effective blood volume (1500 - 2000 ml) the\ncompensatory mechanisms begin to fail and hypotension, tachycardia\nand low urine output (&lt;0.5ml/kg/hr in adults) are seen.</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Grade 4</th>\n<td>At 40-50% loss of blood volume (2000-2500 ml) profound\nhypotension will develop and if prolonged will cause end-organ\ndamage and death.</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 34-year-old man is admitted to hospital complaining of passing\ndark black stools. He is drowsy and a little confused.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is icteric, has conjunctival pallor and\nseveral spider naevi. His pulse rate is 98 beats per minute and the\nblood pressure is measured at 101/75 mmHg.</p>\n\n<p>His abdomen is moderately distended with shifting dullness.\nRectal examination reveals an empty rectum with a small amount of\nsoft, dark black stool on the glove. He has already been\ncatheterised and has passed 54 mls of urine in the last hour.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>112 g/L</td>\n<td>(130 - 180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>67 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150 - 400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.3</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>129 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137 - 144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>3.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5 - 4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>12.3 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>54 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 110)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the most appropriate fluid replacement strategy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398192\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199807\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398192\"><span>5% dextrose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398194\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199807\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398194\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Transfusion of fresh frozen plasma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398195\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199807\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398195\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Transfusion of packed red cells</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398193\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199807\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398193\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">No fluid resuscitation necessary</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398191\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199807\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398191\"><span>0.9% sodium chloride</span></div></div>",
        "id": 133
    },
