        "correctAnswerIndex": 0,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Prothrombin complex concentrate and vit K</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>GI haemorrhage</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Fresh frozen plasma (FFP) contains more dilute clotting factors and therefore produces inferior correction and should not be used in the management of life-threatening bleeding (unless prothrombin complex concentrate is not available).</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This gentleman is having a potentially life-threatening bleed in\nthe setting of a grossly elevated INR.</p>\n\n<p>Due to his warfarin therapy, he will have reduced levels of\nfactors II, VII, IX, and X and requires replacement to correct his\nINR rapidly. This is most effectively achieved by the\nadministration of prothrombin complex concentrate (Beriplex or\nOctaplex, 25-50 units/kg IV) and vitamin K.</p>\n\n<p>These result in complete reversal of the warfarin-induced\nanticoagulation within 10 minutes, but the clotting factors have a\nfinite half-life and therefore 5 mg IV vitamin K should be given at\nthe same time.</p>\n\n<p>Fresh frozen plasma (FFP) contains more dilute clotting factors\nand therefore produces inferior correction and should not be used\nin the management of life-threatening bleeding (unless prothrombin\ncomplex concentrate is not available).</p>\n\n<p>Cryoprecipitate and oral vitamin K are not recommended for the\nmanagement of life-threatening bleeding.</p>\n\n<p><strong>Reference:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Keeling D, et al. <a href=\"http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/21671894\" target=\"_blank\">Guidelines on oral anticoagulation with warfarin -\nfourth edition.</a> <cite>Br J Haematol.</cite>\n2011;154:311-24.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 70-year-old male is admitted with haematemesis and\nhypotension. He is currently being treated with warfarin for atrial\nfibrillation and his INR returns as 10.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate immediate\ntreatment of his INR?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117897\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80725\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117897\"><span>Prothrombin complex concentrate and vit K</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117896\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80725\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117896\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oral vitamin K</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117894\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80725\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117894\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Fresh frozen plasma</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117893\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80725\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117893\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cryoprecipitate</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117895\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80725\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117895\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Intravenous vitamin K</span></div></div>",
        "id": 137
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Intravenous crystalloid</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>For the initial resuscitation of patients with an upper GI bleed\ntake an ABC, that is, airway, breathing, circulation approach.\nEstablish good intravenous access ideally two 14-16 G cannulae in\nthe antecubital fossae. If there is haemodynamic compromise,\nadminister colloid or crystalloid and review the response. The\nhaemoglobin may not fall immediately as this occurs only after\nreactive plasma volume expansion and haemodilution. If there is\nsignificant bleeding cross-match 2-8 units.</p>\n\n<p>In cases of massive exsanguinating blood loss and delay in the\navailability of cross-matched blood, administer uncross-matched\ngroup O Rh negative packed red cells.</p>\n\n<p>Do not attempt insertion of a central venous pressure (CVP) line\nbefore initial resuscitation as failure and complications are more\nlikely - use large-bore peripheral cannulae. A CVP line can be\nconsidered at a later stage in major haemorrhage especially if\nthere is poor response to initial resuscitation.</p>\n\n<p>This patient has portal hypertension and he has presented with\nwhat is likely to be an acute variceal bleed. Terlipressin is\nimportant in the management of variceal bleeds. Give 2 mg IV stat\nfollowed by 1- 2 mg every four to six hours for 72 hours or until\nthe bleeding stops. It is contraindicated in patients with known\nvascular disease or an ischaemic ECG. Terlipressin helps control\nhaemorrhage and may reduce mortality but it does not replace the\nnecessity for endoscopy.</p>\n\n<p>In a suspected acute variceal haemorrhage endoscopy should be\nperformed as soon as possible - ideally this should be once the\npatient has been resuscitated and is haemodynamically stable but\nthis may not be achievable in someone who continues actively to\nbleed from their varices.</p>\n\n<p>Call the gastroenterologist on call immediately. An anaesthetist\nwill need to be involved as there is a risk of aspiration in the\ncases of major haemorrhage or in encephalopathic patients -\nintubation prior to endoscopy is almost invariably required.</p>\n\n<div>Reference:</div>\n\n<p>Bloom S, Webster G. <em>Oxford Handbook of Gastroenterology and\nHepatology.</em> 2nd ed. Oxford: Oxford University Press; 2006.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old man presents with frank haematemesis. He does not\nspeak English therefore you are unable to obtain a history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is shocked with a heart rate of 110 beats per\nminute and a blood pressure of 95/70 mmHg. There is evidence of\npalmar erythema and spider naevi. Abdominal examination reveals\nascites and splenomegaly with epigastric tenderness.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the next best step in the immediate\nmanagement of this patient?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397979\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199764\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397979\"><span>Terlipressin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397980\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199764\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397980\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Upper GI endoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397976\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199764\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397976\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Cross-matched blood</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397977\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199764\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397977\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">CVP line insertion</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397978\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199764\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397978\"><span>Intravenous crystalloid</span></div></div>",
        "id": 138
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Aorto-enteric fistula</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has evidence of massive and ongoing\ngastrointestinal haemorrhage. The size of the bleed and presence of\nforeign material in the aorta (in the form of an aortic graft)\nmakes a diagnosis of aorto-enteric fistula likely.</p>\n\n<p>Fistula formation often occurs in the setting of infection of\nprosthetic material (more frequently in open than endovascular\nrepairs) and the pyrexia and raised inflammatory markers in this\ncase may indicate this.</p>\n\n<p>Whilst a peptic ulcer remains in the differential the torrential\nnature of the bleeding, combined with the previous history of an\n<a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/145\">abdominal aortic aneurysm</a> repair, makes it less likely than an\naorto-enteric fistula. In fact the majority of peptic ulcer bleeds\nsettle spontaneously.</p>\n\n<p><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/815\">Oesophageal varices</a> also present with torrential\ngastrointestinal bleeding however the likelihood that they\nrepresent the underlying pathology in this case is very small due\nto the absence of symptoms, signs or biochemical evidence of portal\nhypertension.</p>\n\n<p>Diverticular bleeds may be very severe however the appearance is\nusually of fresh red blood.</p>\n\n<p>Dieulafoy's lesions are the result of a tortuous submucosal\narteriole eroding through the gastric mucosa. Presentation is\nusually with intermittent gastrointestinal bleeding and repeated\nnormal endoscopies (as lesions are typically very difficult to\nspot). Overall Dieulafoy's lesions are a rare cause of\ngastrointestinal haemorrhage.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 72-year-old man presents with epigastric pain and passing\ndark, red-black stool.</p>\n\n<p>He has a previous history of atrial fibrillation, ischaemic\nheart disease, open repair of an aortic aneurysm and intermittent\nclaudication. His medications include aspirin, simvastatin and\nlisinopril.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is pale and clammy, heart rate is 150 beats\nper minute and irregular, blood pressure 65/40 mmHg and temperature\n37.8\u00b0C. His abdomen is diffusely tender, particularly in the\nepigastrum and a pulsatile, expansile mass can be felt. He is\npassing melaena continuously.</p>\n\n<p>His blood tests reveal that:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>42 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>14.3 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>556 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Sodium</th>\n<td>143 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Potassium</th>\n<td>5.1 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>33.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>214 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>What is the likely underlying diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398367\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199842\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398367\"><span>Dieulafoy's lesion</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398368\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199842\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398368\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Diverticular bleed</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398366\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199842\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398366\"><span>Aorto-enteric fistula</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398369\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199842\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398369\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastric ulcer</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398370\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199842\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398370\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oesophageal varices</span></div></div>",
        "id": 139
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Discharge</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>FAP can involve the upper GI tract especially the duodenum, and\nmalignancy can occur. Oesophagogastroduodenoscopy (OGD)\nsurveillance is recommended. In this case there is no abnormality\nnoted.</p>\n\n<p>Upper gastrointestinal bleeding can be scored (Rockall) and\ndivided into high and low risk.</p>\n\n<p>The most likely diagnosis here is alcohol induced <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/816\">gastritis</a> or a\nMallory-Weiss tear. There are no features of concern here and he\ncan safely be discharged. The patient would need further\ninvestigation if there was ongoing blood loss.</p>\n\n<p>The <a href=\"http://gut.bmj.com/content/38/3/316.full.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">Rockall score</a> indicates the risk of death after\nacute upper gastrointestinal haemorrhage. The score can be used\nwith or without the results of endoscopy or emergency surgery.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>An 18-year-old man was seen on a Friday night at the Emergency\nDepartment. He had been brought in by his friends who reported that\nhe had collapsed in a public bar after vomiting. Friends had noted\nthat the vomitus was bright red.</p>\n\n<p>He reported a history of familial adenomatous polyposis (FAP)\nfor which he had undergone a prophylactic colectomy with the\nformation of an ileoanal pouch some years previously.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he looked well, blood pressure 120/80 mm/Hg with\nno postural drop, pulse rate 70 beats per minute. The remainder of\nthe examination including per rectal examination was\nunremarkable.</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>139 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White blood cells</th>\n<td>6 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>200 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An upper gastrointestinal (GI) endoscopy was normal.</p>\n\n<p>Which should be the next step in his management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118111\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118111\"><span>Referral to surgical team</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118109\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118109\"><span>Discharge</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118108\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118108\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Colonoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118112\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118112\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Repeat upper gastrointestinal endoscopy</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118110\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80768\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118110\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Enteroscopy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 140
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Varices</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This patient has stigmata of chronic liver disease with signs of\nportal hypertension, and together with frank haematemesis this is\nlikely to be an acute variceal haemorrhage.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 38-year-old man presents with frank haematemesis. He does not\nspeak English therefore you are unable to obtain a history.</p>\n\n<p>On examination he is shocked with a heart rate of 110 beats per\nminute and a blood pressure of 95/70 mmHg. There is evidence of\npalmar erythema and spider naevi. Abdominal examination reveals\nascites and splenomegaly with epigastric tenderness.</p>\n\n<p>What is the most likely diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397974\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397974\"><span>Peptic ulcer disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397972\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397972\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastritis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397973\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397973\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Mallory-Weiss tear</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397975\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397975\"><span>Varices</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"397971\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199763\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"397971\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Angiodysplasia</span></div></div>",
        "id": 141
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 3,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Duodenal ulcer</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The most likely explanation is a duodenal ulcer based upon the\nfact that this patient has clearly lost a significant proportion of\nhis circulating volume (postural hypotension, tachycardia, and\napproximtately 6-7 g/dL drop in haemoglobin).&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>The aspirin may be coincidental or has helped to precipitate\nbleeding in a pre-existing lesion.&nbsp;<em>H.pylori</em> is the most\nlikely causative agent for the ulcer.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Gastric erosions would not be an adequate explanation for such\nmarked circulating volume loss.</p>\n\n<p>Chronic usage of aspirin is associated with oesophagitis and\nalso an increased risk of ulcer formation (often gastric).</p>\n\n<p>Malignancy is unlikely because of history of being fit and also\nthe age.&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>Angiodysplasia is a comparatively infrequent cause of large\nacute upper GI haemorrhage.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A previously well 40-year-old man is admitted with a single\nhaematemesis after taking 300 mg of aspirin five hours\npreviously.</p>\n\n<p>On examination, pulse was 120/min with a blood pressure of\n110/75 mmHg (lying) and 90/60 mmHg (standing). Respiratory and\nabdominal examination were otherwise normal. His haemoglobin\nconcentration returned as 70 g/L (130-180).</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most likely cause of his\nhaematemesis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117688\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117688\"><span>Angiodysplasia</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117691\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117691\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastric erosions</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117692\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117692\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oesophagitis</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117689\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117689\"><span>Duodenal ulcer</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117690\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80684\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117690\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastric cancer</span></div></div>",
        "id": 142
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>IV Terlipressin</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The answer here is terlipressin.&nbsp; Alternative agents are\noctreotide (a somatostatin analogue) and somatostatin itself,\nalthough these are no longer in widespread use.</p>\n\n<p>Nitrates are never used as monotherapy, but used in conjunction\nwith vasopressin not desmopressin.</p>\n\n<p>Propranolol is used only as prophylaxis and not in an\nemergency.</p>\n\n<p>Omeprazole is useful only in peptic ulcerations.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 54-year-old man with Child-Pugh grade C chronic liver disease\npresents with haematemesis.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate immediate\ntherapy?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117675\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80681\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117675\"><span>IV Omeprazole</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117673\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80681\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117673\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">IV Desmopressin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117677\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80681\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117677\"><span>IV Terlipressin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117676\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80681\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117676\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">IV Propranolol</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117674\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80681\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117674\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">IV Isoket</span></div></div>",
        "id": 143
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 1,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>History of renal failure</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The Rockall score is used to help determine the prognosis of\nupper gastrointestinal bleeds. Increasing scores are strongly\ncorrelated with increasing risk of mortality, correlation with risk\nof re-bleeding is also present but not as strong.</p>\n\n<p>The score consists of five categories:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>age</li>\n\n<li><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1013\">shock</a></li>\n\n<li>co-morbidity</li>\n\n<li>diagnosis and</li>\n\n<li>evidence of bleeding (the latter two can only be categorised\nafter endoscopy).</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Each category is scored between 0 and 2 points, with the\nexception of comorbitities which has a maximum score of 3. The\nweighting of points corresponds to the additional risk of death\nthat parameter confers. Renal failure, liver failure and metastatic\ncancer carry the highest points, and thus confer the highest risk\nof death, of any of the other parameters included in the scoring\nsystem.</p>\n\n<p>An endoscopic finding of gastric ulcer confers a single point.\nThe haemoglobin level is not included within the Rockall scoring\nsystem. It is included within an alternative scoring system known\nas the Blatchford score. In this system a haemoglobin less than 10\ng/dl (in a woman) scores six points, the highest number of points\nawarded for a single parameter, however this score was designed to\npredict the need for intervention (for example, transfusion,\nendoscopy) not to predict mortality.</p>\n\n<p>A previous history of ischaemic heart disease confers two points\nand age 60-79 confers a single point. The full Rockall scoring\nsystem is shown in the table below:</p>\n\n<table class=\"table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td style=\"border:none; background:none;\">&nbsp;</td>\n<th>Score 0</th>\n<th>Score 1</th>\n<th>Score 2</th>\n<th>Score 3</th>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Age</th>\n<td>&lt;60</td>\n<td>60-79</td>\n<td>&gt;80</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1013\">Shock</a></th>\n<td>No <a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1013\">shock</a></td>\n<td>Pulse &gt;100</td>\n<td>Systolic blood pressure &lt;100 mmHg</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Co-morbidity</th>\n<td>Nil major</td>\n<td>&nbsp;</td>\n<td>CCF, IHD, major morbidity</td>\n<td>Renal or liver failure, metastatic cancer</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Diagnosis</th>\n<td><a class=\"bp-link\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"https://bestpractice.bmj.com/topics/en-gb/1145\">Mallory-Weiss tear</a></td>\n<td>All other diagnoses</td>\n<td>GI malignancy</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Evidence of bleeding</th>\n<td>None</td>\n<td>-</td>\n<td>Blood, adherent clot, spurting vessel</td>\n<td>-</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 79-year-old woman presents with melaena. She has been passing\ndark, black tarry stools for the last 36 hours.</p>\n\n<p>Her past medical history includes chronic renal failure\n(baseline creatinine 247 \u00b5mol/L) and angina. Her medications\ninclude aspirin, isosorbide mononitrate, ramipril, calcium\ncarbonate, alfacalcidol and erythropoietin.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she is sweaty and clammy with a pulse rate of 102\nbeats per minute and blood pressure of 102/43 mmHg.</p>\n\n<p>Her blood tests show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>79 g/L</td>\n<td>(115 - 165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Urea</th>\n<td>41 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5 - 7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Creatinine</th>\n<td>320 \u00b5mol/L</td>\n<td>(60 - 110)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>INR</th>\n<td>1.2</td>\n<td>(&lt;1.4)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Her upper GI endoscopy reveals a gastric ulcer with a visible,\nnon-bleeding vessel and no blood in the stomach.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the features in her clinical history listed below\nconfers the greatest risk of mortality?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398187\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199806\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398187\"><span>Endoscopic finding of gastric ulcer</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398190\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199806\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398190\"><span>History of renal failure</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398186\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199806\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398186\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Age of 79 years</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398189\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199806\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398189\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">History of ischaemic heart disease</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"398188\" name=\"rdBtnOption+199806\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"398188\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Haemoglobin 79 g/L</span></div></div>",
        "id": 144
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Urgent referral to on-call surgeons</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>GI haemorrhage</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Surgical management should be considered where endoscopic intervention has failed.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>This lady has lost a lot of blood and has ongoing bleeding\ndespite endoscopic intervention. She requires urgent surgery and\noversewing of the bleeding vessel. Interventional radiology for\nembolisation of the vessel would be a potential alternative route\nthat could be considered depending upon availability of the service\nand the patient's operative risk.</p>\n\n<p>It would be appropriate to use omeprazole postoperatively to\npromote ulcer healing. Omeprazole will not stop bleeding from a\nvisible vessel.</p>\n\n<p>Terlipressin and octreotide decrease portal blood pressure and\nhave an established role in variceal haemorrhage, but not in peptic\nulcer disease.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 76-year-old lady had a GI bleed 10 months ago related to NSAID\nuse for osteoarthritis. At that time an endoscopy showed a duodenal\nulcer which was treated. She now represents with an acute\nhaematemesis following re-prescription of diclofenac with\nmisoprostol.</p>\n\n<p>Her haemoglobin on admission is 56 g/L. OGD is performed,\nshowing a single bleeding vessel on the posterior wall of the\nduodenum. Adrenaline injection and clipping fail to control the\nbleeding.</p>\n\n<p>Which is the next step in her management?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117730\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80692\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117730\"><span>Octreotide</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117731\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80692\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117731\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Repeat endscopy the next day</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117732\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80692\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117732\"><span>Urgent referral to on-call surgeons</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117729\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80692\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117729\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">IV Omeprazole</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117728\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80692\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117728\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Terlipressin</span></div></div>",
        "id": 145
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 2,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Aorto-enteric fistula</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>GI haemorrhage</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Considering the potential complications of major abdominal surgery.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>The upper GI endoscopy is normal, therefore GU, gastric\nerosions, varices, and Mallory-Weiss syndrome are unlikely.</p>\n\n<p>The strongly positive faecal occult blood (FOB) suggests\nsignificant GI haemorrhage.</p>\n\n<p>Aorto-enteric fistulae (AEF) are now known to occur following\nendovascular repair of abdominal aortic aneurysms (AAA) and\nsecondary to aortic grafting of any kind, presumably because of\nmechanical forces of dislodged or migrating devices.</p>\n\n<p>This patient may well have had an aorto-bifemoral graft as\ntreatment for peripheral vascular disease.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 78-year-old female with diabetes presented with a two day\nhistory of melaena and dizziness. She had taken an unknown\nanalgesic four days previously.</p>\n\n<p>On examination she was pale with a pulse of 90 beats per minute,\na blood pressure of 100/65 mmHg, and a lower midline scar from an\noperation for intermittent claudication three months\npreviously.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>80 g/L</td>\n<td>(130-180)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Faecal occult blood</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Strongly positive</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Upper gastrointestinal tract endoscopy</th>\n<td colspan=\"2\">Normal</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which is the most likely cause of her upper gastrointestinal\n(GI) haemorrhage?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118049\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80756\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118049\"><span>Gastric erosions</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118051\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80756\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118051\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Mallory-Weiss syndrome</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118048\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80756\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118048\"><span>Aorto-enteric fistula</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118050\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80756\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118050\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Gastric ulcer</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118052\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80756\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118052\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oesophageal varices</span></div></div>",
        "id": 146
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Terlipressin</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>GI haemorrhage</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>Terlipressin causes splanchnic vasoconstriction.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Terlipressin causes splanchnic vasoconstriction, thereby\nrestricting bleeding from varices which is the likely cause of\nbleeding in this patient.</p>\n\n<p>In the acute gastrointestinal bleed described above, glypressin\nis the best treatment to aid cardiovascular resuscitation. Beta\nblockade comes into play later in order to treat portal\nhypertension chronically.</p>\n\n<p>Lactulose should be considered to guard against progression of\nencephalopathy.</p>\n\n<p>OGD should be considered but full resuscitation and optimal\nmedical management should be attempted in the first instance.</p>\n\n<p>In the event of ascites, ciprofloxacin is used as prophylaxis\nagainst spontaneous bacterial peritonitis. This is of secondary\nimportance here.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 70-year-old male presents with haematemesis and melaena.</p>\n\n<p>His presenting blood pressure is 80/46 mmHg, with a heart rate\nof 114 bpm. He is known to have idiopathic cirrhosis and there is\nmild encephalopathy.</p>\n\n<p>You start to resuscitate him with colloid, blood, FFP, and\ndextrose.</p>\n\n<p>Which of the following is the most appropriate next step at this\nmoment?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117935\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80733\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117935\"><span>OGD</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117934\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80733\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117934\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Oral beta blockers</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117933\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80733\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117933\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Ciprofloxacin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117937\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80733\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117937\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Lactulose</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117936\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80733\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117936\"><span>Terlipressin</span></div></div>",
        "id": 147
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Colonoscopy</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n    <div class=\"alert alert-warning fontsize14 w-100\">\n        <span class=\"fontsize18\">Key Learning Points</span>\n        \n\n        \n\n\n\n        <p>GI haemorrhage</p>\n\n        <ul>\n                <li>In the older age group, investigation of the lower gastrointestinal (GI) tract is vital to exclude a lower GI malignancy in cases such as unexplained anaemia with bowel signs or symptoms. Colonoscopy would have the greatest diagnostic yield in most settings.</li>\n        </ul>\n        \n        \n\n        <div>\n            <label id=\"KLPSuccessMsg\" style=\"display:none\" class=\"text-success fontsize14\">Your preference has been recorded successfully.</label>\n        </div>\n    </div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>In the older age group, investigation of the lower\ngastrointestinal (GI)&nbsp;tract is vital to exclude a lower GI\nmalignancy.</p>\n\n<p>There is an association between aortic stenosis and\nangiodysplasia; it has been debated and is likely to be present but\nweak. Angiodysplasia is more common in severe aortic disease and\nmay regress upon treatment of the valvular lesion.</p>\n\n<p>There is evidence that angiodysplasia is more frequently present\nin patients with aortic stenosis compared to those with other\nvalvular dysfunction, and also that patients with aortic stenosis\nare over-represented in those with occult GI bleeding. This,\nhowever, does not extrapolate to mean that angiodysplasia is the\nmost common underlying lesion in patients with aortic stenosis and\nGI bleeding.</p>\n\n<p>Colonoscopy would have the greatest diagnostic yield in this\nsetting.</p>\n\n<p>After this, capsule endoscopy would probably be the most\nappropriate.</p>\n\n<p>Mesenteric angiography may be useful if there is active\nbleeding; generally, a large arteriovenous malformation or a\nbleeding rate of at least 0.5 ml/min is required to obtain a\ndiagnostic scan.</p>\n\n<p>CT scans do not demonstrate colonic pathology as well as\ncolonoscopy, which is still considered the gold standard.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 67-year-old man with known aortic valvular disease is admitted\nwith deteriorating dyspnoea.</p>\n\n<p>Investigations show:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>90 g/L</td>\n<td>(120-160)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>MCV</th>\n<td>70 fL</td>\n<td>(80-96)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Upper gastrointestinal tract endoscopy</th>\n<td>Normal</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Duodenal biopsy</th>\n<td>Normal</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>Which one of the following investigations is most likely to\nprovide the diagnosis?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117918\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80730\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117918\"><span>Barium enema</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117921\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80730\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117921\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Mesenteric angiography</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117922\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80730\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117922\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Small bowel enema</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117920\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80730\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117920\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">CT abdomen</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"117919\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80730\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"117919\"><span>Colonoscopy</span></div></div>",
        "id": 148
    },
    {
        "correctAnswerIndex": 4,
        "exp": "\n                                <div class='correct-answer-div'>\n                                    <span class='text'>Correct answer : </span>\n                                    <span>Restart the aspirin with proton pump inhibitor cover</span>\n                                </div>\n                            \n    \n\n    <div>\n                \n    </div>\n\n    \n\n    <div id=\"errorDiv\" class=\"errorMessage fontsize14 p-2\" style=\"display:none\"></div>\n\n<div>\n</div>            <span class=\"fontsize18\">Explanation</span>\n            <div class=\"answerExplanation\"><p>Given her age and comorbidity this lady would be at high risk\n(Rockall score) in the event of a further bleed.</p>\n\n<p>Aspirin carries significant benefit for her. Evidence indicates\nthat discontinuing aspirin, even in the setting of an acute upper\ngastrointestinal (GI) bleed, exposes patients to greater risks due\nto adverse cardiovascular events. NICE guidelines on acute upper GI\nbleeding advocate that aspirin should be restarted once haemostasis\nhas been achieved in order to mitigate against this.</p>\n\n<p>The fact that she is <em>H. pylori</em> positive allows us to\naddress an important risk factor for peptic ulcer disease. <em>H.\npylori</em> eradication is &gt;90%successful, however in her case\nyou may want to recheck.</p>\n\n<p>Given that she is now two months out from her bleed this is not\na reason to delay reintroduction of her aspirin especially with the\nadded protection of a PPI.</p>\n\n<p>Serology remains positive for many years, repeat endoscopy is\nunnecessary.</p></div>\n        \n",
        "question": "<div class=\"questionWrapper\"><p>A 69-year-old lady was seen in the medical admissions ward. She\npresented with coffee ground vomiting and melaena stool on the day\nof admission.</p>\n\n<p>Although she had vomited coffee grounds only once she had passed\nthree melaena stools. She had a past history of significant\nischaemic heart disease for which she took aspirin, atenolol,\nramipril and simvastatin. She did not consume alcohol and had not\nsmoked since her myocardial infarction ten years previously.</p>\n\n<p>On examination at the time of admission she was pale. Blood\npressure was 95/55 mmHg pulse 60 beats per minute. Heart sounds\nwere normal, the chest was clear and abdomen soft, non tender with\nno masses. Melaena stool was seen per rectum</p>\n\n<p>Investigations revealed:</p>\n\n<table class=\"marginTop table table-bordered\">\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<th>Haemoglobin</th>\n<td>85 g/L</td>\n<td>(115-165)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>White cell count</th>\n<td>7.2 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(4-11)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Platelets</th>\n<td>200 \u00d710<sup>9</sup>/L</td>\n<td>(150-400)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum sodium</th>\n<td>140 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(137-144)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum potassium</th>\n<td>4.2 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(3.5-4.9)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum urea</th>\n<td>14 mmol/L</td>\n<td>(2.5-7.5)</td>\n</tr>\n\n<tr>\n<th>Serum creatinine</th>\n<td>60 \u03bcmol/L</td>\n<td>(60-110)</td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>\n\n<p>An upper gastrointestinal endoscopy revealed a duodenal ulcer. A\nbiopsy from the gastric antrum was positive for urease activity\nwhen tested in the endoscopy department. She was given one week of\namoxicillin 1 gm twice daily, clarithromycin 500 mg twice daily and\nomeprazole 20 mg twice daily as <em>Helicobacter pylori</em>\neradication therapy.</p>\n\n<p>Two months later in the follow up clinic a letter from her\ncardiologist was noted in which he asked whether the aspirin could\nbe restarted.</p>\n\n<p>What course of action is most appropriate?</p></div><div class=\"questionOptions options\"><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118102\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80766\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118102\"><span>Withhold aspirin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118098\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80766\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118098\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Check <em>Helicobacter pylori</em> serology and treat if positive,\nthen restart the aspirin with proton pump inhibitor cover</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118099\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80766\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118099\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Repeat the upper gastrointestinal endoscopy and repeat antral\nbiopsy for a urease test, treat if positive then restart the\naspirin with proton pump inhibitor</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118101\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80766\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118101\"><span class=\"textNotSelected\">Urea breath test, treat if positive then restart the aspirin</span></div><div class=\"option\"><input type=\"radio\" id=\"118100\" name=\"rdBtnOption+80766\" class=\"answer-radio\" value=\"118100\"><span>Restart the aspirin with proton pump inhibitor cover</span></div></div>",
        "id": 149
    }
